          Programming note: Money Stuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monda=
y.=E2=80=9CTitanium=E2=80=9DHere=E2=80=99s a theory. You run a bank, and a =
smallish public company comes to you and asks you to lend it, say, $500 mil=
lion. You say =E2=80=9Cokay I will need to know more about your revenue and=
 expenses and assets,=E2=80=9D and the company says =E2=80=9Cno no no never=
 mind that. Here=E2=80=99s the thing. We have publicly traded stock. We can=
 always issue more of it. Sure the price might go down but then we=E2=80=99=
ll just issue more and more stock; we can always issue=C2=A0any dollar amou=
nt of stock that we want.[1] Right now our market cap is $1 billion and we =
have 100 million shares outstanding at $10 each, but even if the price fall=
s=C2=A0we could issue five billion more shares at $0.10 each, or five trill=
ion more shares at $0.0001 each, or whatever. So we can always raise $500 m=
illion to pay you back; our stock might go down, but a dollar loaned=C2=A0t=
o us will always be worth a dollar. So we are absolutely money-good for $50=
0 million and you should lend it to us at the risk-free rate without inquir=
ing into our collateral or cash flows.=E2=80=9DIs this argument appealing? =
It is wrong, but is it interestingly wrong? Do you read it and say =E2=80=
=9Coh huh sounds like they have a point there, what am I missing,=E2=80=9D =
or do you read it and say =E2=80=9Ccome on that is absurd=E2=80=9D? I don=
=E2=80=99t know how you will experience it. I find it somewhat appealing at=
 an abstract level, though, again,=C2=A0wrong. Also to be fair there are so=
me companies that sometimes =E2=80=A6=C2=A0sort of =E2=80=A6=C2=A0try this?=
 And not with=C2=A0zero=C2=A0success, I mean.[2]=C2=A0Why is it wrong? Well=
 I mean the simplest problem is that there is no actual guarantee that a co=
mpany can issue an infinite number of shares at a positive price.=C2=A0Let=
=E2=80=99s say the company has a net value of $1 billion today, and then it=
 borrows $500 million, and then its factory burns down and its CEO steals t=
he $500 million and it is just a worthless empty shell that owes the bank $=
500 million. It can go out to shareholders and say =E2=80=9Chey we need $50=
0 million to get back to zero, would you like to buy 50 million shares at $=
10 each,=E2=80=9D and they will say no, and it will say =E2=80=9Cwhat about=
 50 billion shares at $0.01 each,=E2=80=9D and they will also say no, and e=
ventually it might find some punters on Reddit who will buy some shares at =
like $0.0001 each =E2=80=94=C2=A0you can find some=C2=A0people to buy anyth=
ing =E2=80=94=C2=A0but not=C2=A0enough=C2=A0of them. If the present value o=
f the company=E2=80=99s future cash flows is negative, its stock will be wo=
rth zero, and almost nobody will pay anything for it.[3]Also,=C2=A0if a com=
pany actually tries this =E2=80=94=C2=A0if it keeps issuing more and more s=
tock at lower and lower prices to pay off some fixed amount of money =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0people=E2=80=99s enthusiasm for the stock will evaporate quickly. =
Nobody wants to keep buying stock as it keeps going down. The technical nam=
e for this form of financing=C2=A0is =E2=80=9Cdeath-spiral financing.=E2=80=
=9DStill there is in a loose sense some truth to the argument. If people su=
stainably want to buy a company=E2=80=99s stock, then that does make its cr=
edit better, because it really can=C2=A0sell stock to pay off its debt. Of =
course if things change =E2=80=94=C2=A0the factory burns down, it stops mak=
ing money, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0they might not want to buy the stock anymore=
. But if you have some thesis like =E2=80=9Cpeople will always want to buy =
this company=E2=80=99s stock even if it runs into a disaster in its busines=
s,=E2=80=9D then you should be more willing to lend it money and expect to =
be paid back at par. I used to call this =E2=80=9CNetflix Theory,=E2=80=9D =
and you would probably have to take something like this into account in dec=
iding whether to lend money to, say,  AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc.=C2=A0=
these days. Even if AMC=E2=80=99s business does poorly, if it can keep issu=
ing stock to willing buyers then it is not going to run into any real finan=
cial problems. There is no guarantee of that, but if it is true it might be=
 true for meme reasons rather than cash-flow reasons. =E2=80=9CPeople will =
buy our stock because they will buy our stock, so we can always pay back ou=
r debts=E2=80=9D might be more or less true even though it doesn=E2=80=99t =
make much sense.The next step is to separate this theory entirely from cash=
 flows, companies, etc. Just like: =E2=80=9CWe have issued shares of nothin=
g, and as long as people continue to buy those shares of nothing at some po=
sitive price, our debt will always be money-good.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The way an =
algorithmic stablecoin works is that somebody creates two cryptocurrency=C2=
=A0tokens, let=E2=80=99s call them Dollarcoin and Sharecoin. And they write=
 a white paper that says =E2=80=9CDollarcoins=C2=A0will always be worth $1,=
 and if they are ever worth less than $1 we will print some Sharecoins=C2=
=A0and sell them to buy Dollarcoins until the price of Dollarcoins=C2=A0goe=
s back to=C2=A0$1, and we can always print an arbitrary number of Sharecoin=
s and sell them for a positive amount of money and use the money to buy Dol=
larcoins, so Dollarcoins will always be worth a dollar.=E2=80=9D There is g=
enerally a great deal more hand-waving involved than that,[4] but that=E2=
=80=99s the economic heart of it.=C2=A0Is this argument appealing? It is wr=
ong, but is it interestingly wrong?Anyway lol:Iron Titanium token (TITAN), =
the share token of a one-time multibillion-dollar decentralized finance (De=
Fi) protocol, has fallen to near zero.The token was last seen changing hand=
s for around $0.000000035, down from Wednesday=E2=80=99s high of $65. The f=
allout, which has been swift, has brought the project to its knees. ...The =
project was attempting to boot a partially collateralized stablecoin known =
as IRON. The stablecoin, in turn, consists of Circle and Coinbase=E2=80=99s=
 stablecoin USDC (-0.08%) as well as TITAN and was pegged to $1. Stablecoin=
s are cryptocurrencies whose value is attached to financial assets such as =
commodities or government-issued currency in a bid to keep them =E2=80=9Cst=
able.=E2=80=9DIn the case of IRON, which receives its collateral backing fr=
om TITAN, users may mint new stablecoins through a mechanism on Iron Financ=
e=E2=80=99s network by locking up 25% in TITAN and 75% in USDC.Due to how t=
he tokenomics of this particular DeFi project functions, when new IRON stab=
lecoins are minted, the demand for TITAN increases, driving up its price. C=
onversely, when the price of TITAN falls dramatically, as was the case on W=
ednesday evening, the peg becomes unstable.=E2=80=9CTITAN=E2=80=99s price w=
ent to $65 and then pulled back to $60. This caused whales to start selling=
,=E2=80=9D Fred Schebesta, founder of Finder.com.au and Iron Finance invest=
or, told CoinDesk via Telegram. =E2=80=9CThat then led to a big de-pegging =
of [IRON]=E2=80=9DAs whales (large bag holders) began to offload their TITA=
N tokens, they flooded the market with excess tokens, causing a bank run. A=
 bank run refers to a situation when a large portion of users attempt to wi=
thdraw their money at the same time believing the bank, or in this case, th=
e protocol, will cease to exist.In turn, as TITAN began to fall in dramatic=
 fashion so did the pegged value of IRON. As whale dumps further decreased =
the value of IRON, it triggered the stablecoin=E2=80=99s mechanism that min=
ts TITAN and removes liquidity in a bid to stabilize IRON to $1.This caused=
 an arbitrage opportunity in the difference in price of IRON and TITAN, whi=
ch in turn flooded the market with even more TITAN tokens adding additional=
 sell pressure and destabilizing IRON=E2=80=99s price even further.=E2=80=
=9CIt was a crypto vortex of money,=E2=80=9D said Schebesta.In the beginnin=
g, users were receiving an incredible 2%-5% annual percentage rate per day.=
 When the dust settled, TITAN was near zero and IRON was last seen trading =
way off peg, around $0.69.If the price of IRON goes down from $1 (good) to =
$0.95 (bad), you just issue some TITAN (worth $65) to buy some IRON until i=
t=E2=80=99s worth $1 again. And if=C2=A0IRON keeps going down, you just iss=
ue some more TITAN (worth $60) and buy more. And if IRON keeps going down =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0[you can fill in some more iterations here] =E2=80=A6=C2=A0y=
ou just keep issuing TITAN (worth $0.000000035) and at that point you=E2=80=
=99re not accomplishing much. If you could sell 286 trillion TITAN at=C2=A0=
$0.000000035 each you=E2=80=99d raise $10=C2=A0million. That=E2=80=99s prob=
ably hard. There are 285 million IRON (formerly worth $1) outstanding.=C2=
=A0I am oversimplifying the IRON mechanism =E2=80=94=C2=A0really it=E2=80=
=99s partially algorithmic and partially collateralized by USDC, which is i=
n turn a collateralized stablecoin; you can read more about its creation an=
d redemption mechanics here =E2=80=94 but not, I think, in an essential way=
. The core of an algorithmic stablecoin is that you have some=C2=A0other=C2=
=A0token that is not meant to be=C2=A0stable, but that is meant to support =
the stablecoin by being arbitrarily=C2=A0issuable. It doesn=E2=80=99t matte=
r if Titanium is worth $65 or $0.65, as long as you can always issue a few =
million dollars=E2=80=99 worth of it. But you can=E2=80=99t, not always, an=
d that does matter.Anyway go to the IRON website and Medium page quick, bef=
ore they take down all these boasts about=C2=A0how stable it is:Market shoc=
ks provide the best stress tests for stablecoin pegs, and IRON=E2=80=99s st=
rong peg retention should go a long way to grow trust in our community. IRO=
N has shown itself to be a shock-proof stablecoin, and the stabilizing prot=
ocol is now battle-hardened.Shock-proof! Battle-hardened! Also here=E2=80=
=99s a Medium post titled =E2=80=9CTITAN and STEEL Emerge As Bear-Proof Ass=
ets,=E2=80=9D oops oops oops:Over the past few weeks, as market conditions =
worsened for crypto as a whole, TITAN and STEEL have stood out as gems. Whi=
le the rest of the market fell, with BTC declining around 50% from its rece=
nt highs, TITAN and STEEL have both risen 1,000% in value in a relatively s=
hort period of time. These price movements make TITAN and STEEL two of the =
best performing bear-proof assets in the entire crypto market.Oh well.Also =
apparently Mark Cuban lost money on this thing and  now thinks he should no=
t have been allowed to do that.Bill Ackman Pornhub activismHere=E2=80=99s a=
 strange little story about how Bill Ackman read a New York Times article a=
bout Pornhub, thought it was bad, and texted and tweeted that the big credi=
t-card companies should stop working with Pornhub. And then they did. Is th=
is=C2=A0because=C2=A0Ackman texted them? Nobody quite says that, but nobody=
 quite denies it either, and I suppose it=E2=80=99s not really in anyone=E2=
=80=99s interest to deny it. One activist who spent lots of time trying to =
engage the credit-card companies, Leila Mickelwait,=C2=A0does give Ackman c=
redit:=E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s an unlikely advocate that you wouldn=E2=80=99t =
normally think of using his platform to push for that change, but I mean, l=
ook what that did,=E2=80=9D she says. =E2=80=9CBill pulled the leverage of =
the Mastercard relationship, and he called out Visa and Discover. And then,=
 suddenly, there=E2=80=99s reaction from the card companies, and Pornhub de=
leted 80 percent of their website.=E2=80=9DMickelwait adds, =E2=80=9CIt jus=
t shows the power of finance, of financial pressure. It wasn=E2=80=99t unti=
l Bill really laid on the pressure and said, =E2=80=98Do the right thing,=
=E2=80=99 that they did.=E2=80=9DSo good=C2=A0job, Bill Ackman, or whatever=
.Bill Ackman does a lot of shareholder activism at his day job, and has mad=
e a lot of money=C2=A0from it, but this one was on the house.=C2=A0He did t=
his activism for free,=C2=A0without expecting any profit. He doesn=E2=80=99=
t even own the stocks:An influential shareholder activist, Ackman immediate=
ly thought about the growing interest in ethical, or ESG, investing.And tha=
t=E2=80=99s where the billionaire hedge fund titan =E2=80=94 who has unseat=
ed several corporate CEOs in his career =E2=80=94 saw an opening. In this c=
ase, he wasn=E2=80=99t an investor in any of the publicly traded companies =
that he knew were profiting from Pornhub=E2=80=99s content, which is often =
uploaded from users the same way individuals post videos on YouTube. =E2=80=
=A6=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s shareholder money that fuels this activity,=E2=80=
=9D says Ackman. He points out that while the environmental and governance =
efforts of ESG =E2=80=94 or environmental, social, and governance investing=
 =E2=80=94 get a lot of attention, the =E2=80=9CS=E2=80=9D part =E2=80=9Cha=
s come in third.=E2=80=9DHe notes, =E2=80=9CLots of companies say that they=
=E2=80=99re really great with ESG issues, but they=E2=80=99ve got to look a=
 little deeper.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0One thing that I want to point out is that, i=
f you were the chief executive officer of a public company and wanted=C2=A0=
to rank the people with the power to influence your environmental, social a=
nd governance policies, a partial ranking, in ascending order of importance=
, might go something like this:5. A social activist like Leila Mickelwait, =
a person who cares about environmental or social=C2=A0issues and writes and=
 talks about them.4. A shareholder-proposal=C2=A0activist, a person who buy=
s 100 shares of your stock and submits a nonbinding shareholder proposal as=
king you to write a report about the issue.3. Your biggest shareholders, if=
 they are=C2=A0index-y investors like BlackRock Inc. who talk a lot about E=
SG stuff.2. Your medium-sized institutional shareholders, if they are activ=
e investors who might dump your stock if they don=E2=80=99t like what you=
=E2=80=99re up to.1. A famous activist investor who=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t ow=
n any of your stock.If you are the chief executive officer of a public comp=
any, Bill Ackman is more likely to get you fired than BlackRock is, even if=
 BlackRock owns 7% of your stock and Bill Ackman owns zero. After all, if y=
ou anger Bill Ackman, he might decide to=C2=A0buy=C2=A0stock and start a pr=
oxy fight to fire you. If you anger=C2=A0BlackRock, it=E2=80=99s not=C2=A0g=
oing to sell any stock and it isn=E2=80=99t going to start a proxy fight. O=
f course if you anger BlackRock, Bill Ackman =E2=80=94=C2=A0or  Engine No. =
1 =E2=80=94=C2=A0might start a proxy fight, and then BlackRock with its 7% =
stake might support the proxy fight and you might end up fired. You have to=
 keep your big shareholders happy as insurance against activists. But you c=
an keep activists happy as insurance against activists too.Everyone vaguely=
 knows about this in the context of financial performance and capital-struc=
ture optimization, and so a few years ago you could read lots of stories ab=
out how companies were buying back stock and spinning off non-core division=
s and generally doing the things that activists would want=C2=A0even if the=
re was no activist in their stock. The point was to avoid attracting the at=
tention of activists by doing what they wanted anyway. You did not read qui=
te those sorts of stories about ESG[5]: Polluting or being racist or whatev=
er might be=C2=A0bad, they might attract negative attention from various st=
akeholders=C2=A0(customers, employees, regulators, BlackRock), but they wer=
e not conceived of as things that would attract negative attention=C2=A0fro=
m activist hedge funds. Activist hedge funds were busy pushing for stock bu=
ybacks.But then last month activist hedge fund Engine No.=C2=A01 LLC  did a=
 proxy fight against Exxon Mobil Corp. that focused on environmental issues=
, and won, and replaced  three members of Exxon=E2=80=99s board of director=
s, and now the ESG activist space looks very different. Now ESG issues are =
a wedge that activist hedge funds can use to persuade big institutional inv=
estors and win proxy fights, and activist-hedge-fund-led proxy fights are a=
 tool that institutional investors can use to enforce their ESG goals. So i=
f you run a public company and Bill Ackman calls you about an ESG topic, yo=
u listen.


