ttom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px 5px;">=E2=80=9CTitanium=
=E2=80=9D</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a theory. You run=
 a bank, and a smallish public company comes to you and asks you to lend it=
, say, $500 million. You say =E2=80=9Cokay I will need to know more about y=
our revenue and expenses and assets,=E2=80=9D and the company says =E2=80=
=9Cno no no never mind that. Here=E2=80=99s the thing. We have publicly tra=
ded stock. We can always issue more of it. Sure the price might go down but=
 then we=E2=80=99ll just issue more and more stock; we can always issue=C2=
=A0<em>any dollar amount of stock that we want</em>.[1] Right now our marke=
t cap is $1 billion and we have 100 million shares outstanding at $10 each,=
 but even if the price falls=C2=A0we could issue five billion more shares a=
t $0.10 each, or five trillion more shares at $0.0001 each, or whatever. So=
 we can always raise $500 million to pay you back; our stock might go down,=
 but a dollar <em>loaned=C2=A0</em>to us will always be worth a dollar. So =
we are absolutely money-good for $500 million and you should lend it to us =
at the risk-free rate without inquiring into our collateral or cash flows.=
=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is this argument appealing? It is=
 wrong, but is it interestingly wrong? Do you read it and say =E2=80=9Coh h=
uh sounds like they have a point there, what am I missing,=E2=80=9D or do y=
ou read it and say =E2=80=9Ccome on that is absurd=E2=80=9D? I don=E2=80=99=
t know how you will experience it. I find it somewhat appealing at an abstr=
act level, though, again,=C2=A0wrong. Also to be fair there are some compan=
ies that sometimes =E2=80=A6=C2=A0sort of =E2=80=A6=C2=A0try this? And not =
with=C2=A0<em>zero=C2=A0</em>success, I mean.[2]=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">Why is it wrong? Well I mean the simplest problem is that there=
 is no actual guarantee that a company can issue an infinite number of shar=
es at a positive price.=C2=A0Let=E2=80=99s say the company has a net value =
of $1 billion today, and then it borrows $500 million, and then its factory=
 burns down and its CEO steals the $500 million and it is just a worthless =
empty shell that owes the bank $500 million. It can go out to shareholders =
and say =E2=80=9Chey we need $500 million to get back to zero, would you li=
ke to buy 50 million shares at $10 each,=E2=80=9D and they will say no, and=
 it will say =E2=80=9Cwhat about 50 billion shares at $0.01 each,=E2=80=9D =
and they will also say no, and eventually it might find some punters on Red=
dit who will buy some shares at like $0.0001 each =E2=80=94=C2=A0you can fi=
nd <em>some=C2=A0</em>people to buy anything =E2=80=94=C2=A0but not=C2=A0<e=
m>enough=C2=A0</em>of them. If the present value of the company=E2=80=99s f=
uture cash flows is negative, its stock will be worth zero, and almost nobo=
dy will pay anything for it.[3]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also,=C2=A0=
if a company actually tries this =E2=80=94=C2=A0if it keeps issuing more an=
d more stock at lower and lower prices to pay off some fixed amount of mone=
y =E2=80=94=C2=A0people=E2=80=99s enthusiasm for the stock will evaporate q=
uickly. Nobody wants to keep buying stock as it keeps going down. The techn=
ical name for this form of financing=C2=A0is =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24178706.269431/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
